    "long_instructions": "# Flex Property\r\n\r\nThis is the shorthand for `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink` and `flex-basis` combined. \r\n\r\nThe default for `flex` is `0 1 auto` which sets the `flex-grow` to `0`, the `flex-shrink` to `1`, and the `flex-basis` to `auto`. An easy way to think of this is imagining you are setting the \"max\", \"min\", and \"ideal size\". \r\n\r\nThe second and third parameters (`flex-shrink` and `flex-basis`) are optional. This means that you _can_ set `flex` with a single number value, like `flex: 5;`. But, if you do this, that changes the `flex-basis` to `0%`, so itâ€™s like setting `flex-grow: 5;`, `flex-shrink: 1;`, and `flex-basis: 0%;`.\r\n\r\n_Check out the previous challenge level or the \"Help & Tips\" tab to learn about `flex-basis`!_\r\n\r\n# Do This\r\n\r\n**In the CSS file:**\r\n1. Add the `flex-basis` property to the first container and set value to `auto`\r\n2. Add the `flex-basis` property to the second container and set value to `150px`\r\n\r\n**In the HTML file:**\r\n1. Add some more text to **one** of the paragraph in the **\"basis-auto\"** container to see the item sizes adjusting based on the content. Try adding a line break to see how the container size adjusts.\r\n   * _This is the default for all Flex items._\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**Don't forget to refer back to your <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lrkMGcPwjKo4g5uyvVfaXpFb7kRUfdtqcsqLRtaDWYM/edit?usp=sharing\">Flexbox Children Cheat Sheet</a> when needed!**\r\n\r\n",
    "mini_rubric": "false",
